    <edge id="e0" source="Glucose" target="G3P">
      <data key="edge_sign">positive</data>
      <data key="edge_color">#228B22</data>
      <data key="edge_confidence">MEDIUM</data>
      <data key="edge_mechanism">Glucose enters PTS then Pgi-driven EMP glycolysis, supplying G3P as a DXS substrate.</data>
      <data key="edge_doi">10.3390/molecules25143136</data>
      <data key="edge_evidence">glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate (G3P) and pyruvate are condensed to form 1-deoxy-d-xylulose-5-phosphate (DXP) by DXP synthase (DXS)</data>
    </edge>
    <edge id="e1" source="Glucose" target="Pyruvate">
      <data key="edge_sign">positive</data>
      <data key="edge_color">#228B22</data>
      <data key="edge_confidence">MEDIUM</data>
      <data key="edge_mechanism">Glucose glycolysis terminates in pyruvate, the second DXS substrate.</data>
      <data key="edge_doi">10.3390/molecules25143136</data>
      <data key="edge_evidence">deletion of the zwf gene encoding glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase (G6PD)...resulted in the increased carbon fluxes in the Embden-Meyerhof-Parnas (EMP) pathway and indirectly led to an increase in lycopene production</data>
    </edge>
    <edge id="e2" source="Glycerol" target="G3P">
      <data key="edge_sign">positive</data>
      <data key="edge_color">#228B22</data>
      <data key="edge_confidence">MEDIUM</data>
      <data key="edge_mechanism">Glycerol is phosphorylated then oxidised to DHAP/G3P, enriching G3P relative to pyruvate.</data>
      <data key="edge_doi">10.3390/molecules25143136</data>
      <data key="edge_evidence">Glycerol is a viable carbon source for beta-carotene and lycopene production, as it increases glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate and pyruvate, which are imperative intermediates in central carbon metabolism extension to the MEP pathway</data>
    </edge>
    <edge id="e3" source="Xylose" target="G3P">
      <data key="edge_sign">positive</data>
      <data key="edge_color">#228B22</data>
      <data key="edge_confidence">MEDIUM</data>
      <data key="edge_mechanism">Xylose feeds the pentose-phosphate shunt producing F6P and G3P for MEP.</data>
      <data key="edge_doi">10.3390/molecules25143136</data>
      <data key="edge_evidence">Xylose is another viable carbon source that feeds glycolysis via xylose isomerase and xylulokinase, supplying pyruvate and G3P to the MEP pathway</data>
    </edge>
    <edge id="e4" source="Xylose" target="Pyruvate">
      <data key="edge_sign">positive</data>
      <data key="edge_color">#228B22</data>
      <data key="edge_confidence">MEDIUM</data>
      <data key="edge_mechanism">Xylose catabolism terminates in pyruvate via EMP.</data>
      <data key="edge_doi">10.3390/molecules25143136</data>
      <data key="edge_evidence">Xylose is another viable carbon source that feeds glycolysis via xylose isomerase and xylulokinase, supplying pyruvate and G3P to the MEP pathway</data>
    </edge>
    <edge id="e5" source="PGI" target="G3P">
      <data key="edge_sign">positive</data>
      <data key="edge_color">#228B22</data>
      <data key="edge_confidence">MEDIUM</data>
      <data key="edge_mechanism">Pgi (phosphoglucose isomerase) routes G6P into the EMP branch feeding G3P.</data>
      <data key="edge_doi">10.1128/AEM.02155-15</data>
      <data key="edge_evidence">Deletion of pgi and zwf was found to eliminate catabolite repression as well as the ability of E. coli to consume glucose for biomass formation, and the yield from glucose of the bioproduct D-glucaric acid was significantly increased in a delta-pgi delta-zwf strain</data>
    </edge>
    <edge id="e6" source="PGI" target="Pyruvate">
      <data key="edge_sign">positive</data>
      <data key="edge_color">#228B22</data>
      <data key="edge_confidence">MEDIUM</data>
      <data key="edge_mechanism">Pgi-gated EMP flux terminates in pyruvate.</data>
      <data key="edge_doi">10.1128/AEM.02155-15</data>
      <data key="edge_evidence">Deletion of pgi and zwf was found to eliminate catabolite repression as well as the ability of E. coli to consume glucose for biomass formation</data>
    </edge>
    <edge id="e7" source="ZWF" target="G3P">
      <data key="edge_sign">negative</data>
      <data key="edge_color">#DC143C</data>
      <data key="edge_confidence">MEDIUM</data>
      <data key="edge_mechanism">Zwf diverts G6P into the oxidative PPP, reducing G3P supply to DXS; Δzwf raises lycopene ~130%.</data>
      <data key="edge_doi">10.3390/biom13121747</data>
      <data key="edge_evidence">knockout of the zwf gene, significantly enhanced lycopene production by over 130%</data>
    </edge>
    <edge id="e8" source="GAPA" target="G3P">
      <data key="edge_sign">negative</data>
      <data key="edge_color">#DC143C</data>
      <data key="edge_confidence">MEDIUM</data>
      <data key="edge_mechanism">GapA (GAPDH) drains G3P into 1,3-bisPG in lower glycolysis.</data>
      <data key="edge_doi">10.1038/75398</data>
      <data key="edge_evidence">the distribution between pyruvate and glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate (G3P), the originating precursors of the isoprenoid pathway, is a major factor that can limit isoprenoid production yields in E. coli, with alterations in the central metabolism that redirect flux from pyruvate back to G3P enhance lycopene production</data>
    </edge>
    <edge id="e9" source="PYKA" target="Pyruvate">
      <data key="edge_sign">positive</data>
      <data key="edge_color">#228B22</data>
      <data key="edge_confidence">MEDIUM</data>
      <data key="edge_mechanism">PykA (pyruvate kinase II) converts PEP to pyruvate.</data>
      <data key="edge_doi">10.3390/molecules25143136</data>
      <data key="edge_evidence">deleting pyruvate kinases-I and -II (Pyk-I and-II)...lycopene production was significantly increased</data>
    </edge>
    <edge id="e10" source="PYKF" target="Pyruvate">
      <data key="edge_sign">positive</data>
      <data key="edge_color">#228B22</data>
      <data key="edge_confidence">MEDIUM</data>
      <data key="edge_mechanism">PykF (major pyruvate kinase) converts PEP to pyruvate.</data>
      <data key="edge_doi">10.3390/molecules25143136</data>
      <data key="edge_evidence">deleting pyruvate kinases-I and -II (Pyk-I and-II)...lycopene production was significantly increased</data>
    </edge>
    <edge id="e11" source="PPS" target="Pyruvate">
      <data key="edge_sign">negative</data>
      <data key="edge_color">#DC143C</data>
      <data key="edge_confidence">MEDIUM</data>
      <data key="edge_mechanism">Pps (PEP synthase) drains pyruvate back to PEP, reducing pyruvate pool for DXS.</data>
      <data key="edge_doi">10.3390/biom13121747</data>
      <data key="edge_evidence">overexpressing phosphoenolpyruvate (PEP) synthase (PPS)...achieved a 250% increase in lycopene production by...diverting flow from pyruvate to G3P</data>
    </edge>
    <edge id="e12" source="PPS" target="G3P">
      <data key="edge_sign">positive</data>
      <data key="edge_color">#228B22</data>
      <data key="edge_confidence">MEDIUM</data>
      <data key="edge_mechanism">Pps-driven pyruvate→PEP redirection ultimately raises upstream G3P availability (Farmer 2000 flux rebalance).</data>
      <data key="edge_doi">10.1038/75398</data>
      <data key="edge_evidence">alterations in the central metabolism that redirect flux from pyruvate back to G3P enhance lycopene production</data>
    </edge>
    <edge id="e13" source="EDD" target="G3P">
      <data key="edge_sign">positive</data>
      <data key="edge_color">#228B22</data>
      <data key="edge_confidence">MEDIUM</data>
      <data key="edge_mechanism">Edd (6-PG dehydratase) produces KDPG that Eda splits into G3P + pyruvate (Entner-Doudoroff).</data>
      <data key="edge_doi">10.1186/s12934-015-0301-x</data>
      <data key="edge_evidence">The ED pathway is a shortcut for G3P and pyruvate generation. It produces the two MEP precursors in equal amounts via a four-step reaction from G6P.</data>
    </edge>
    <edge id="e14" source="EDD" target="Pyruvate">
      <data key="edge_sign">positive</data>
      <data key="edge_color">#228B22</data>
      <data key="edge_confidence">MEDIUM</data>
      <data key="edge_mechanism">ED pathway via Edd supplies pyruvate stoichiometrically with G3P, matching DXS 1:1 substrate need.</data>
      <data key="edge_doi">10.1186/s12934-015-0301-x</data>
      <data key="edge_evidence">The ED pathway is a shortcut for G3P and pyruvate generation. It produces the two MEP precursors in equal amounts via a four-step reaction from G6P.</data>
    </edge>
    <edge id="e15" source="EDA" target="G3P">
      <data key="edge_sign">positive</data>
      <data key="edge_color">#228B22</data>
      <data key="edge_confidence">MEDIUM</data>
      <data key="edge_mechanism">Eda (KDPG aldolase) splits KDPG into G3P + pyruvate.</data>
      <data key="edge_doi">10.1186/s12934-015-0301-x</data>
      <data key="edge_evidence">The ED pathway is a shortcut for G3P and pyruvate generation. It produces the two MEP precursors in equal amounts via a four-step reaction from G6P.</data>
    </edge>
    <edge id="e16" source="EDA" target="Pyruvate">
      <data key="edge_sign">positive</data>
      <data key="edge_color">#228B22</data>
      <data key="edge_confidence">MEDIUM</data>
      <data key="edge_mechanism">Eda-generated pyruvate matches the ED 1:1 stoichiometry required by DXS.</data>
      <data key="edge_doi">10.1186/s12934-015-0301-x</data>
      <data key="edge_evidence">The ED pathway is a shortcut for G3P and pyruvate generation. It produces the two MEP precursors in equal amounts via a four-step reaction from G6P.</data>
    </edge>
    <edge id="e17" source="LDH" target="Pyruvate">
      <data key="edge_sign">negative</data>
      <data key="edge_color">#DC143C</data>
      <data key="edge_confidence">MEDIUM</data>
      <data key="edge_mechanism">Ldh (lactate dehydrogenase) drains pyruvate to lactate under microaerobic growth.</data>
      <data key="edge_doi">10.3390/molecules25143136</data>
      <data key="edge_evidence">lactate production pathways</data>
    </edge>
    <edge id="e18" source="ACEE" target="Acetyl_CoA">
      <data key="edge_sign">positive</data>
      <data key="edge_color">#228B22</data>
      <data key="edge_confidence">MEDIUM</data>
      <data key="edge_mechanism">AceE (PDH E1) is the pyruvate→Acetyl-CoA entry point feeding TCA and MVA.</data>
      <data key="edge_doi">10.3390/molecules25143136</data>
      <data key="edge_evidence">knockout of aceE would presumably improve carbon flux to pyruvate and formate, and further deletion of fdhF</data>
    </edge>
    <edge id="e19" source="PTA" target="Acetyl_CoA">
      <data key="edge_sign">negative</data>
      <data key="edge_color">#DC143C</data>
      <data key="edge_confidence">MEDIUM</data>
      <data key="edge_mechanism">Pta drains Acetyl-CoA via acetyl-P to overflow acetate.</data>
      <data key="edge_doi">10.3390/molecules25143136</data>
      <data key="edge_evidence">deletion of the acetate and lactate production pathways...elimination of the acetate pathway</data>
    </edge>
    <edge id="e20" source="PPC" target="Acetyl_CoA">
      <data key="edge_sign">negative</data>
      <data key="edge_color">#DC143C</data>
      <data key="edge_confidence">MEDIUM</data>
      <data key="edge_mechanism">Ppc (PEP carboxylase) diverts PEP toward OAA, reducing the upstream supply feeding AceE and Acetyl-CoA.</data>
      <data key="edge_doi">10.3390/molecules25143136</data>
      <data key="edge_evidence">overexpressing Ppc and Pck to introduce the bypass pathway between PEP and pyruvate via the oxaloacetate and TCA cycle</data>
    </edge>
    <edge id="e21" source="Glucose" target="Acetyl_P">
      <data key="edge_sign">positive</data>
      <data key="edge_color">#228B22</data>
      <data key="edge_confidence">MEDIUM</data>
      <data key="edge_mechanism">Glucose-driven glycolysis produces acetyl-P as a signalling metabolite for the NtrC branch.</data>
      <data key="edge_doi">10.3390/molecules25143136</data>
      <data key="edge_evidence">ACP, an indicator of glucose flux</data>
    </edge>
    <edge id="e22" source="Acetyl_P" target="NRI">
      <data key="edge_sign">positive</data>
      <data key="edge_color">#228B22</data>
      <data key="edge_confidence">MEDIUM</data>
      <data key="edge_mechanism">Acetyl-P phosphorylates NRI (NtrC) in the absence of the dedicated kinase.</data>
      <data key="edge_doi">10.3390/molecules25143136</data>
      <data key="edge_evidence">NRI...capable of sensing the level of acetyl phosphate (ACP), an indicator of glucose flux</data>
    </edge>
    <edge id="e23" source="NRI" target="PPS">
      <data key="edge_sign">positive</data>
      <data key="edge_color">#228B22</data>
      <data key="edge_confidence">MEDIUM</data>
      <data key="edge_mechanism">NRI-P activates pps promoter (Alper 2005 sigma-S-family screen).</data>
      <data key="edge_doi">10.1038/75398</data>
      <data key="edge_evidence">recruited and altered the Ntr regulon (a global regulatory system in Escherichia coli) to control the engineered lycopene biosynthesis pathway</data>
    </edge>
    <edge id="e24" source="NRI" target="IDI">
      <data key="edge_sign">positive</data>
      <data key="edge_color">#228B22</data>
      <data key="edge_confidence">MEDIUM</data>
